SharpSerializer is an open source XML and binary serializer for .NET Framework, .NET Compact Framework and Silverlight. It needs no type definitions nor type mappings to serialize data. It is especially usefull for tombstoning - i.e. binary serialization to isolated storage in WP7 (Windows Phone 7). With only one line of code it can serialize types like: Multidimensional array, nested array, array-of-arrays, polymorphic object (where value type is inherited from the declared type), generic type, generic listing (i.e. Dictionary, Collection) and many more... Refer to http://www.sharpserializer.com for details.
summary: Open source XML and binary serializer for .NET Full, Compact and Silverlight/WP7 (Windows Phone 7)

Tinyweb is a lightweight web framework for ASP.NET that embraces HTTP and aims to be ridiculously simple. Tinyweb moves away from the MVC pattern for developing web applications. Instead, you start with separate addressable resources that respond directly to the HTTP method that was used to access the resource. Every resource is a class and every implemented HTTP method (get, post, put, delete) is a method on the class. With Tinyweb, you're writing code that is conceptually close to the way HTTP actually works.
summary: Tinyweb is a lightweight web framework for ASP.NET that embraces HTTP and aims to be ridiculously simple.

Chocolatey - think executables/application packages (like apt-get for Windows), not library packages. This is what the Chocolatey NuGet goodness is for.
Chocolatey allows you to install application nuggets and run executables from anywhere.  
||Executable Nuggets| For example, say you have an executable in the tools folder of your package named bob.exe. Then you can type
'chocolatey install yourPackageName [-source source] [-version version]' OR 'cinst yourPackageName [-source source] [-version version]'
and when it finishes you can type
'bob'
and it will run your application executable.  
||Application Nuggets - Full on double rainbow|| For example, say you type 
'chocolatey install 7zip [-source source] [-version version]' OR 'cinst 7zip [-source source] [-version version]' 
- when it finishes you will have installed 7zip on your machine (in your add/remove programs).
summary: Chocolatey is your machine level NuGet repository. Think apt-get for Windows (executables/application packages), not library packages.

The RemoteReader plugin allows the ImageResizer to resize and display images that are located at arbitrary URLs. Kind of like a resizing relay.

There are 3 layers of security to prevent abuse. 

1. The API signs the remote url with HMAC SHA-256 to prevent anyone from tampering or generating them without access to the signing key.
2. A whitelist approach is taken to sites. By default, no sites are allowed. You must handle the RemoteReaderPlugin.Current.AllowRemoteRequest event to permit sites (or portions of sites) to be relayed.
4. The  plugin requires that all remote images be decoded and re-encoded. Files are never returned as-is. This ensures that the files are valid images, and prevents XSS attacks.

Please note, you must configure the <remotereader signingKey="to a long and secure pass phrase" /> and set <remotereader allowAllSignedRequests="true" /> if all code calling RemoteReaderPlugin.Current.CreateSignedUrl(remoteUrl,settings) is trusted.
Visit http://imageresizing.net for details, documenation, and free support. 
E-mail support@imageresizing.net if you encounter any problems with the software. 
The documentation for this plugin resides at http://imageresizing.net/plugins/remotereader

Nvergent is primarily designed to be used with ASP.NET MVC 3 applications, but it can be used with any application type (although not all diagnostic features will be available).

Tinyweb is a lightweight web framework for ASP.NET that embraces HTTP and aims to be ridiculously simple. Tinyweb moves away from the MVC pattern for developing web applications. Instead, you start with separate addressable resources that respond directly to the HTTP method that was used to access the resource. Every resource is a class and every implemented HTTP method (get, post, put, delete) is a method on the class. With Tinyweb, you're writing code that is conceptually close to the way HTTP actually works.

description:
Chocolatey - think executables/application packages (like apt-get for Windows), not library packages. This is what the Chocolatey NuGet goodness is for.
Chocolatey allows you to install application nuggets and run executables from anywhere.  
||Executable Nuggets| For example, say you have an executable in the tools folder of your package named bob.exe. Then you can type
'chocolatey install yourPackageName [-source source] [-version version]' OR 'cinst yourPackageName [-source source] [-version version]'
and when it finishes you can type
'bob'
and it will run your application executable.  
||Application Nuggets - Full on double rainbow|| For example, say you type 
'chocolatey install 7zip [-source source] [-version version]' OR 'cinst 7zip [-source source] [-version version]' 
- when it finishes you will have installed 7zip on your machine (in your add/remove programs).  
|| Check out the WIKI in the project URL for all the details of what you can do with chocolatey!
summary: Chocolatey is your machine level NuGet repository. Think apt-get for Windows (executables/application packages), not library packages.
